===Etymology===
From Scottish English, as past participle of {{term|preve|lang=en}}, a {{etyl|enm|en}} variant of {{term|prove|lang=en}}<ref name="ahd">{{R:American Heritage 2000|prove}}</ref><ref name="mw">{{R:Merriam Webster Online|prove}}</ref> – compare {{term|woven|lang=en}} (from {{term|weave|lang=en}}) and {{term|cloven|lang=en}} (from {{term|cleave|lang=en}}),<ref name="ahd" /> both of which feature ''-eve'' → ''-oven''. {{term||preve}} died out in England, but survived in Scotland, where '''proven''' developed, initially in a legal context, as in “The jury ruled that the charges were not proven.”<ref name="ahd" /> See [[#Usage notes|usage notes]] for historical usage patterns.

Earlier, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|probo|probō|test, try, examine, approve, show to be good or fit, prove|pos=verb|lang=la}}, from {{term|probus||good, worthy, excellent|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|pro-bhwo-||being in front, prominent|lang=ine-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|pro-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|per-||toward|lang=ine-pro}} + {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|bhu-||to be|lang=ine-pro}}.

