====Usage notes====
As the past participle of {{term|prove|lang=en}}, '''proven''' is often proscribed, with {{term|proved|lang=en}} preferred – “have proved” rather than “have proven”. However, today in everyday use they are both used, about equally.<ref name="ahd"/><ref name="mw"/>

Historically, ''proved'' is the older form, while '''proven''' arose as a Scottish variant – see [[#Etymology|etymology]]. Used in legal writing from mid 17th century, it entered literary usage more slowly, only becoming significant in the 19th century, with the poet {{w|Alfred, Lord Tennyson}} among the earliest frequent users (presumably for reasons of meter).<ref name="mw"/> In the 19th century, '''proven''' was widely proscribed, and remained significantly less common through the mid 20th century (''proved'' being used approximately four times as often), by the late 20th century it came to be used about equally.<ref name="mw"/>

As an attributive adjective, '''proven''' is much<ref name="mw"/> more commonly used,<ref name="ahd"/> and {{term|proved|lang=en}} is widely considered an error – “a proven method”, not *“a proved method”.

